Livija Vasiliauskaite

2026-01-27

Data Pre-processing Steps

Before further analysis, the following data pre-processing steps were taken:

  • Fixed IP_ID formatting mismatch in dat_obligor data set. Some IDs appeared with a dash (i.e., DVO_426 instead of DVO426), which was removed.

  • Removed most incomplete duplicate rows from dat_arrangement (i.e., row with most NAs was removed)

  • Data sets containing portfolio details (dat_obligor, dat_arrangement, dat_scoring) were joined taking dat_scoring as the base one, since the data set was most complete

  • Fixed data types of the following variables according to the description given: PD_POOL as factor, AR_ID as character, EDUCATION as factor

  • Several observations with abnormally highly DPD (number of past due days during last 24 months) were observed. Values exceeding 730 (max days per 24 months) were replaced by NAs to reflect possible recording/calculation error. Important note: later in the analysis this variable is capped at a pre-specified value given in the task, this is not changed.

  • Most notably, for the portfolio summary and model/estimate evaluation, a new portfolio subset, defined as the at-risk set, was created by removing subsequent YEARAR_ID pairs once an arrangement is marked as having defaulted within the next 12 months. The rationale behind this approach is that, since the data are reported at year-end, a deal marked as defaulting within 12 months should already be considered defaulted in the following year. If this assumption holds, including arrangements that have already defaulted in the dataset could be misleading, as the goal is to predict defaults and assess overall portfolio risk. Keeping already-defaulted deals could distort portfolio statistics and model evaluation by inflating the number of defaults. The newly defined at-risk set is used as the primary dataset for further analysis unless stated otherwise.

Task: Provide opinion on data quality in terms of completeness, accuracy, consistency.

As briefly mentioned in the previous section, the provided data sets exhibit several issues commonly observed in financial data, where variables are collected from multiple sources and at different points in time. These include inconsistencies in obligor identifier formatting, unrealistically high values of DPD, duplicate rows, and several hundred arrangements appearing in the scoring data set but not in the arrangement-level data. These issues were addressed during data pre-processing.

Moreover, the forward-looking default flags seems to be inconsistent: for some agreements the future default is marked for one year but not for the subsequent ones. This could be caused by overlap or delay in reporting. However, the number of such observations is low (approx. 195).

A more significant issue relates to data completeness. Approximately 22% of all data cells contain missing values in the original full portfolio set. Missingness is highly concentrated in two variables: DPD and M_LAST_DPD, for which around 88% of observations are missing.

Thus, while data is reasonably accurate and consistent after pre-processing, high number of missing values in the main risk attributes raises significant issues when evaluating portfolio performance.

Overall statistics

The below table provides an initial overview of the at risk portfolio across the observed years. The number of arrangements and obligors remains broadly stable over time. More relevantly, the number of arrangements defaulting within the future 12 months (a forward-looking default indicator) varies substantially across years.

Overall, the proportion of defaulting arrangements in the portfolio is relatively small compared to non-defaulting ones, which is relevant for model evaluation, as it implies class imbalance.

The debt ratio distribution is moderately skewed toward higher values; smaller values are more common. The average debt ratio is approximately 0.35, while the median is below 0.25, indicating that half of the portfolio has relatively low debt ratio. This distribution remains stable across the observed years.

The number of days past due during the last 24 months (DPD) is highly right-skewed. The majority of arrangements has very low values, while a small number of observations display large outliers. Mean values range between 13 days, depending on the year. Although the shape of the distribution is consistent across years, it should be noted that 2023 contains fewer observations.

For the number of months since the last past due event, the distribution is centered around 7 months, with no pronounced skewness and relatively stable summary statistics across years, though, as mentioned before, fewer observations are available for 2023. Overall, past due days for the portfolio appear to be few and far between.

Obligor Characteristics

The portfolio composition in terms of obligor age appears stable over time, distributed around a mean age of approximately 51 years, with roughly 75% of observations falling within the 4060 age bracket. Arrangement holders are therefore mostly middle-aged. This is consistently observed across years and further illustrated by the histograms.

It it important to note that these statistics are calculated at the arrangement level rather than the obligor level, thus the obligors with multiple arrangements contribute proportionally more observations. This approach is chosen to reflect age as the potential risk drivers at arrangement level and subsequently how exposed to such risk is the porfolio.

Portfolio composition in terms of arrangement-holder education level is shown in the corresponding plot. Level 3 (university education) is the most common category across all years, while the share of the lowest education level decreases slightly over time. These distributions are weighted by the number of arrangements, not by unique obligors.

Model-Based Risk Measures

The estimated probability of default distribution is highly skewed, with most arrangements assigned extremely low PD values (close to zero), while a smaller subset exhibits values close to one. The distribution appears bimodal, suggesting that either medium-risk arrangements are rare in the portfolio or that the model does not sufficiently differentiate intermediate risk levels. This will is discussed in more detail in the model evaluation section.

Interestingly, looking at the distribution of pooled probability of default, we see clear rise in estimated PD over the years. For 2022 most common PD level/pooled estimate was level 1 (lowest risk), while other levels of risk estimate (mid levels) grew significantly for 2023 and 2024.

Summary

As the first look at the portfolio data, the descriptive statistics suggest that the portfolio is not inherently high-risk. Arrangement holders are mostly middle-aged, on average educational level is relatively high, debt ratios are moderate, and past-due events are not frequent. This is further supported by the relatively low proportion of arrangements defaulting within the forward-looking 12-months.

Relationship Between Risk Drivers and Default Status

Finally, to glimpse at the possible relationship between risk drivers and future default status, boxplots displaying distribution of the risk characteristics by default future default status (1 if defaults within next 12 months and 0 if does not) are presented below.

  • Obligor age does not show meaningful differences between defaulting and non-defaulting arrangements.

  • Debt ratio exhibits slightly higher distributions for defaulting arrangements in 2022 and 2023, suggesting a potential relationship with default risk.

  • Days past due shows a clearly more right-skewed distribution for defaulting arrangements, including extreme values.

  • Months since last past due shows higher values for non-defaulting arrangements in 2022. Unfortunately we do not have enough data to meaninfully compare the distributions for the other years.

Task: Assess correctness of PD estimate calculation.

I interpreted this task as checking whether the provided PD estimates are consistent with the model and data.

The performance of the model, i.e., whether the predictions correspond to the observed data will be checked in the next section.

First, basic sanity checks are performed to evaluate whether the estimates are within the appropriate range [0,1]. Further, PD pool assignment checked, whether is its consistent with the definition provided in the task and if all observations fall into one pool.

No issues were found.

## # A tibble: 5  3

Moreover, probability of default estimates were re-calculated using provided model coefficients and at risk portfolio data. Data was prepared as per provided description:

  • Obligor level maximum number of past due days and minimum number of months since last due were calculated
  • Education levels were dummy encoded
  • NAs were replaced by given values
  • Flooring, capping and scaling for numeric variables was conducted

The re-estimated probabilities of default were then compared to the provided estimates.

Around 10% of the observations in the at risk set has large PD estimation mismatch, i.e., the difference of more than 0.9 in absolute value. Since quick manual re-calculation as a check yielded the same results as the re-calculated estimates, we can assume this mismatch is likely caused by data inconsistencies or missing value replacement. For example, in case where new estimates predict large PD while the given ones - negligible probability of default, the difference might be influenced by missing values in maximum past due days being replaced by 400 - which is a large value that is likely predicting a default.

### Model evaluation

The first look into the models performance is provided by the below table reporting the average predicted probability of default (PD) by realized default status. Defaulting arrangements exhibit higher predicted PDs compared to non-defaulting ones, indicating that the model assigns higher risk estimates to arrangements that default in the future. Therefore, model differentiates risk at the aggregate level.

## # A tibble: 2  2
##   DFLT_FLAG mean_pd
##       <int>   <dbl>
## 1         0 0.00295
## 2         1 0.597

Further analysis of the distribution of predicted probabilities of default by realized future default status reveals notable misclassifications. For non-defaulting arrangements, the predicted PDs are largely concentrated near zero, indicating accurate risk assessments. However, for defaulting arrangements, a substantial proportion of predicted PDs are also near zero, that is, model assigns very low default probability to arrangemnets that subsequently default.

Given that correctly predicting defaults is the primary objective, the model demonstrates limited risk differentiation for defaulting arrangements. This is perhaps not surprising, considering the high proportion of non-defaulting arrangements in the portfolio, which likely results in the model being trained on relatively few default cases.

Also noteworthy that model does not predict any medium risks.

Calibration plot further depicts that model fails to differentiate risk well for mid-range PDs and underestimates risk for these segments, as indicated by high observed default rate for the mid-range PD bins.

Similar conclusions can be drawn from the ROC plot. The model performs well for extreme risk levels: many defaults are identified with few false positives. However, for the moderate-risk arrangements, the model is not as good in differentiating, as indicated by the shallow slope in the mid-range of false positive rate. Some defaults are only captured when allowing a high false positive rate.

Lastly, AUC are calculated. High AUC value indicates that extreme cases are predicted well.

auc(rocCurve)
## Area under the curve: 0.9013

max_dpd_coef <- par_model$ESTIMATE[7]
min_m_dpd_coef <- par_model$ESTIMATE[8] 

# Creating MX DPD and MIN M_LAST_DPD variables per obligor
dat_risk <- dat_risk %>%
  group_by(IP_ID) %>%
  mutate(MAX_DPD = ifelse(all(is.na(DPD_capped)), NA,  max(DPD_capped, na.rm = TRUE)),
         MIN_M_LAST = ifelse(all(is.na(M_LAST_DPD)), NA,min(M_LAST_DPD, na.rm = TRUE))) %>%
  
  ungroup()

# dummy encoding for education

dat_risk <- dummy_cols(
  dat_risk,
  select_columns = "EDUCATION",
  remove_selected_columns = FALSE
)

# Replacing NA's by given values:
dat_evaluation <- dat_risk %>%
  mutate(AGE = ifelse(is.na(AGE), par_model$MISSING_VALUE[2], AGE),
         EDUCATION_1 = ifelse(is.na(EDUCATION_1), par_model$MISSING_VALUE[3], EDUCATION_1),
         EDUCATION_2 = ifelse(is.na(EDUCATION_2), par_model$MISSING_VALUE[4], EDUCATION_2),
         DEBT_RATIO = ifelse(is.na(DEBT_RATIO), par_model$MISSING_VALUE[6], DEBT_RATIO),
         MAX_DPD = ifelse(is.na(MAX_DPD), par_model$MISSING_VALUE[7], MAX_DPD),
         MIN_M_LAST = ifelse(is.na(MIN_M_LAST), par_model$MISSING_VALUE[8], MIN_M_LAST))


# FLOORING/CAPPING AND SCALING numeric variables (values are given)
cap_floor <- function(x, min, max) {
  x[x < min] <- min
  x[x > max] <- max
  x
}

scale_fixed <- function(x, mean, sd) {
  (x - mean) / sd
}

dat_evaluation <- dat_evaluation %>%
  mutate(AGE = cap_floor(AGE, par_model$MIN[2], par_model$MAX[2]),
         DEBT_RATIO = cap_floor(DEBT_RATIO, par_model$MIN[6], par_model$MAX[6]),
         MAX_DPD  = cap_floor(MAX_DPD, par_model$MIN[7], par_model$MAX[7]),
         MIN_M_LAST = cap_floor(MIN_M_LAST, par_model$MIN[8], par_model$MAX[8]))

dat_evaluation <- dat_evaluation %>%
  mutate(AGE = scale_fixed(AGE, par_model$MEAN[2], par_model$ST.DEV[2]),
         DEBT_RATIO =scale_fixed(DEBT_RATIO, par_model$MEAN[6], par_model$ST.DEV[6]),
         MAX_DPD  = scale_fixed(MAX_DPD, par_model$MEAN[7], par_model$ST.DEV[7]),
         MIN_M_LAST = scale_fixed(MIN_M_LAST, par_model$MEAN[8], par_model$ST.DEV[8]))


# Re-calculating:
dat_evaluation <- dat_evaluation %>%
  mutate(PD_recalc = 1 / (1 + exp(-(Intercept + Age_coef*AGE + debt_coef*DEBT_RATIO 
                                    + max_dpd_coef*MAX_DPD + min_m_dpd_coef*MIN_M_LAST +
                                      Educ_coef_1*EDUCATION_1 + Educ_coef_2*EDUCATION_2))))


# Calculating difference:
dat_evaluation <- dat_evaluation %>%
  mutate(PD_diff = PD - PD_recalc)

summary(dat_evaluation$PD_diff)
sd(dat_evaluation$PD_diff, na.rm = TRUE) #LARGE SPREAD
hist(dat_evaluation$PD_diff) 
max(abs(dat_evaluation$PD_diff), na.rm = TRUE) 

# Which rows have large diff
estimation_diff <- dat_evaluation %>%
  filter(abs(PD_diff) > 0.9) %>%
  select(AR_ID, YEAR, PD_recalc, PD_diff)

# Looking them up in original data set
dat_portfolio_diff <- dat_risk %>%
  inner_join(estimation_diff, by = c("AR_ID", "YEAR"))


# around 10% of obs. have mismatch in estimates
nrow(dat_portfolio_diff)/nrow(dat_risk)

# Calibration plot
dat_risk <- dat_risk %>%
  filter(!is.na(PD), !is.na(DFLT_FLAG)) %>%
  mutate(PD_bin = cut(PD,
                      breaks = seq(0, 1, by = 0.1),  
                      include.lowest = TRUE))

calibration <- dat_risk %>%
  group_by(PD_bin) %>%
  summarise(
    mean_PD = mean(PD),
    default_rate = mean(DFLT_FLAG),
    n = n()
  ) %>%
  filter(n > 0)  

ggplot(calibration, aes(x = mean_PD, y = default_rate)) +
  geom_point(size = 3, color = "darkgreen") +
  geom_line(color = "darkgreen") +
  geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0, color = "red", linetype = "dashed") +
  labs(
    title = "PD Calibration Plot",
    x = "Average Predicted PD",
    y = "Observed Default Rate"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()
# ROC curve
rocCurve <- roc(response = dat_risk$DFLT_FLAG,
predictor = dat_risk$PD,
levels = levels(dat_risk$TRUE_D))

auc(rocCurve) # AUC is high - extreme cases are predicted well

plot(rocCurve, legacy.axes = TRUE)
